rComments: MAT378 (Introduction to Real Analysis, now known as 337) is probably the hardest course I have ever taken throughout all of University. Ilia's lectures always had a welcoming environment but at times he went a bit too quick. Is a great person and a great prof, especially if you meet with him in office hours.
Professor Binder is a genius, and this course is fast pacing, but exams are not that difficult. If you work hard, you are guaranteed to get an A!

He's a genius so he teaches very fast. Good if you are smart enough and are looking to challenge yourself. Avoid him however if you are not from math specialist program and only taking some graduate math course because you'll need that for your specialist in the future.

I found that he was really good for MAT315!  His accent does take some time to get use to but  when you do, his classes are interesting and sometimes funny!  He also appoints bonus marks too for solving certain tricky questions.
Likeable, fair, tries to be funny even if he's not so successful at it.  The accent takes some getting used to, but it's worth it because he's great at making course expectations absolutely clear.
did he take his ESL or TOEFFL exams yet?

helpful, intelligent and sexy(always had chalk on his chest). But going too fast in the lecture, do not even have time to copy down notes not mention to undertand it, even though there are 4 students in the class.

MAT378 Foundations of Analysis is one of the hardest math courses in undergraduate years. You will learn lots of pure math stuff and know what math is really about. *The pace of the course is really fast, sometimes you can't even copy everything on the blackboard. Definitely not for faint-hearted.
Going too fast in class, even 4 ppl in class
